      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Patrick J. Lynch, the president of the Patrolmen's Benevolent Association, is making a serious mistake in criticizing Bruce Springsteen over ''American Skin,'' his song about the shooting of Amadou Diallo (news article, June 13). The song's lyrics include repetition of the words ''41 shots.''</p>
        <p>Artists are not supposed to follow strict political lines. They have to speak ''from the gut'' if they are to communicate honestly with the public.</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Patrick J. Lynch, the president of the Patrolmen's Benevolent Association, is making a serious mistake in criticizing Bruce Springsteen over ''American Skin,'' his song about the shooting of Amadou Diallo (news article, June 13). The song's lyrics include repetition of the words ''41 shots.''</p>
        <p>Artists are not supposed to follow strict political lines. They have to speak ''from the gut'' if they are to communicate honestly with the public.</p>
        <p>Furthermore, artists are supposed to shake people out of their complacency, not protect them from embarrassment and controversy. Trying to muzzle those who refer to this tragedy is wrong.</p>
        <p>Mr. Springsteen has generally been a supporter of police officers, giving generously to police charities. Attacks on him are not only unfair but also counterproductive.</p>
        <p>MICHAEL J. GORMAN  Whitestone, Queens, June 13, 2000</p>
        <p>The writer is a New York City police lieutenant.</p>
      </block>
